 but that was explained in the updated bodice front video.

37
00:01:34,340 --> 00:01:38,900
 That is the bodice front instructions uploaded in March 2022.

38
00:01:38,900 --> 00:01:40,980
 There are now three versions

39
00:01:40,980 --> 00:01:43,420
 of my bodice block instructions on YouTube,

40
00:01:43,420 --> 00:01:45,460
 the first two are superseded.

41
00:01:45,460 --> 00:01:47,980
 So make sure that the bodice front you drafted

42
00:01:47,980 --> 00:01:52,020
 was using the instructions uploaded in March 2022,

43
00:01:52,020 --> 00:01:54,740
 and not one of those previous versions.

44
00:01:54,740 --> 00:01:56,940
 I will be using DD again to show the measurements

45
00:01:56,940 --> 00:01:59,860
 to the left while drafting to the right.

46
00:01:59,860 --> 00:02:02,100
 On the left is one of the outcomes of this video,

47
00:02:02,100 --> 00:02:04,820
 that is DD's back sleeveless block.

48
00:02:04,820 --> 00:02:07,380
 On the right is DD's front sleeveless block,

49
00:02:07,380 --> 00:02:09,980
 which makes the sleeveless block set.

50
00:02:09,980 --> 00:02:12,700
 I will actually first draft a middleage for DD,

51
00:02:12,700 --> 00:02:15,260
 then make the adjustments for the sleeveless block,

52
00:02:15,260 --> 00:02:18,660
 then make further adjustments for the sleeved block.

53
00:02:18,660 --> 00:02:20,620
 My recommendation is that you test

54
00:02:20,620 --> 00:02:22,860
 your sleeveless block first.

55
00:02:24,260 --> 00:02:25,700
 This is a comparison to show you

56
00:02:25,700 --> 00:02:27,300
 how different blocks can look,

57
00:02:27,300 --> 00:02:29,140
 so that you are aware that your block

58
00:02:29,140 --> 00:02:30,660
 may look significantly different

59
00:02:30,660 --> 00:02:32,420
 to the one I'm drafting for DD.

60
00:02:32,420 --> 00:02:35,020
 DD's block is to the left, mine is in the middle,

61
00:02:35,020 --> 00:02:36,580
 and on the right one is on top of the other

62
00:02:36,580 --> 00:02:38,100
 to better compare them.

63
00:02:38,100 --> 00:02:39,100
 As should be expected,

64
00:02:39,100 --> 00:02:41,820
 the shape of the block shows you the shape of the person.

65
00:02:41,820 --> 00:02:43,020
 Now having said that,

66
00:02:43,020 --> 00:02:44,620
 you really need the front block as well

67
00:02:44,620 --> 00:02:47,940
 to get a complete picture of the person's shape.

68
00:02:47,940 --> 00:02:50,780
 For example, looking at DD's back block and mine,

69
00:02:50,780 --> 00:02:52,900
 you may think DD has a larger bust,

70
00:02:52,900 --> 00:02:54,620
 and I have a square of figure,

71
00:02:54,620 --> 00:02:57,020
 since DD has 20 centimetres difference

72
00:02:57,020 --> 00:02:59,540
 between her upper bust and waist,

73
00:02:59,540 --> 00:03:01,860
 and I have only 12 centimetres difference

74
00:03:01,860 --> 00:03:03,820
 between my upper bust and waist.

75
00:03:03,820 --> 00:03:05,340
 But this is not taking into account

76
00:03:05,340 --> 00:03:07,220
 the bust measurement and the bust cup,

77
00:03:07,220 --> 00:03:09,940
 and they are more obvious on the bodice front.

78
00:03:09,940 --> 00:03:13,460
 I also have square of shoulders than DD,

79
00:03:13,460 --> 00:03:15,940
 and my torso length is shorter.

80
00:03:15,940 --> 00:03:17,380
 Your block will have differences

81
00:03:17,380 --> 00:03:19,660
 that will reflect your individual measurements

82
00:03:19,660 --> 00:03:21,700
 and your body shape.

83
00:03:21,700 --> 00:03:24,380
 In this video, I'll be drafting the half back,

84
00:03:24,380 --> 00:03:26,300
 which means if any measurements were taken

85
00:03:26,300 --> 00:03:27,700
 across the full back,

86
00:03:27,700 --> 00:03:29,700
 they have to be divided by two.

87
00:03:29,700 --> 00:03:31,660
 If you have an asymmetric figure,

88
00:03:31,660 --> 00:03:33,260
 you may eventually want to figure out

89
00:03:33,260 --> 00:03:34,940
 how each side is different

90
00:03:34,940 --> 00:03:36,500
 and work with the full back

91
00:03:36,500 --> 00:03:39,780
 instead of the half back when drafting your patterns.

92
00:03:39,780 --> 00:03:41,700
 I will be referring to the measurement chart,

93
00:03:41,700 --> 00:03:44,220
 which can be downloaded from my website.

94
00:03:44,220 --> 00:03:46,140
 You will probably already have used it

95
00:03:46,140 --> 00:03:49,220
 to take your measurements and draft the front block.

96
00:03:49,220 --> 00:03:50,540
 If you need another copy,

97
00:03:50,540 --> 00:03:53,260
 there will be a link in the YouTube description box

98
00:03:53,260 --> 00:03:54,380
 below the video.

99
00:03:54,380 --> 00:03:57,740
 Okay, so let's start drafting.

100
00:03:57,740 --> 00:03:59,060
 Firstly, on your paper,

101
00:03:59,060 --> 00:04:01,740
 draw a horizontal line across the bottom of your paper

102
00:04:01,740 --> 00:04:03,220
 to indicate the waist.

103
00:04:03,220 --> 00:04:04,420
 No measurement as yet,

104
00:04:04,420 --> 00:04:06,020
 this is a reference line,

105
00:04:06,020 --> 00:04:09,060
 and we'll start drafting from this point upwards.

106
00:04:09,060 --> 00:04:13,060
 So the first measurement is the full length back.

107
00:04:13,060 --> 00:04:16,420
 This is actually measurement number 23 on my measurement chart.

108
00:04:16,420 --> 00:04:19,540
 It's a first measurement in the back section.

109
00:04:19,540 --> 00:04:22,060
 Using your full length back measurement,

110
00:04:22,060 --> 00:04:24,300
 draw a vertical line from point A

111
00:04:24,300 --> 00:04:27,020
 on your waistline up to point B.

112
00:04:27,020 --> 00:04:29,660
 Make sure the vertical line is at right angles

113
00:04:29,660 --> 00:04:32,060
 to the horizontal waist guideline.

114
00:04:32,060 --> 00:04:34,500
 Mark points A and B.

115
00:04:34,500 --> 00:04:36,420
 The measurement, as shown on DD,

116
00:04:36,420 --> 00:04:38,220
 is taken from the high neck point

117
00:04:38,220 --> 00:04:40,140
 to the waist in a straight line.

118
00:04:40,140 --> 00:04:45,020
 The next measurement is the upper bust arc back,

119
00:04:45,020 --> 00:04:47,580
 measurement number three on the chart.

120
00:04:47,580 --> 00:04:49,660
 The upper bust arc back measurement

121
00:04:49,660 --> 00:04:53,340
 is from side seam to side seam at the underarm level.

122
00:04:53,340 --> 00:04:55,980
 You need to divide the upper bust arc back

123
00:04:55,980 --> 00:04:58,420
 in two for the half block.

124
00:04:58,420 --> 00:04:59,700
 Using that measurement,

125
00:04:59,700 --> 00:05:03,420
 measure across from point B in a straight horizontal line,

126
00:05:03,420 --> 00:05:05,300
 making sure it's at right angles

127
00:05:05,300 --> 00:05:08,940
 to the A to B line and mark point C.

128
00:05:08,940 --> 00:05:11,420
 Then finish the rectangle drawing a line

129
00:05:11,420 --> 00:05:14,820
 from C back down to the waist and mark point D.

130
00:05:14,820 --> 00:05:18,460
 Make sure all the corners are right angles.

131
00:05:18,460 --> 00:05:22,100
 Now to be clear, this is just the body measurement, no ease.

132
00:05:22,100 --> 00:05:24,940
 We will add the ease right at the very end.

133
00:05:24,940 --> 00:05:29,220
 Next is the center back length measurement.

134
00:05:29,220 --> 00:05:31,980
 Measurement number 24 on the chart.

135
00:05:31,980 --> 00:05:33,740
 Using your center back measurement,

136
00:05:33,740 --> 00:05:37,820
 measure up from point A on that A to B line

137
00:05:37,820 --> 00:05:40,180
 and mark point E.

138
00:05:40,180 --> 00:05:43,660
 Then draw a line at right angles to the A to E line

139
00:05:43,660 --> 00:05:48,660
 for about 10 centimetres and mark the end of that line point E2.

140
00:05:48,660 --> 00:05:50,220
 This is just a guideline

141
00:05:50,220 --> 00:05:53,300
 and will help us draw the neck curve later.

142
00:05:53,300 --> 00:05:56,420
 As it's a guideline, it doesn't need to be an exact length,

143
00:05:56,420 --> 00:06:00,420
 which is why I say for about 10 centimetres.

144
00:06:00,420 --> 00:06:04,980
 Next is the across shoulder back measurement number 25

145
00:06:04,980 --> 00:06:06,500
 on the chart.

146
00:06:06,500 --> 00:06:09,700
 Your across shoulder is measured either from the center back

147
00:06:09,700 --> 00:06:14,780
 to the shoulder tip or from shoulder tip to shoulder tip and divided by two.

148
00:06:14,780 --> 00:06:18,140
 Using the half measurement from center back to the shoulder tip,

149
00:06:18,140 --> 00:06:24,220
 measure across from point B towards point C and mark point F.

150
00:06:24,220 --> 00:06:26,060
 Then draw another guideline.

151
00:06:26,060 --> 00:06:27,620
 Again, because it's a guideline,

152
00:06:27,620 --> 00:06:30,020
 it does not need to be an exact length,

153
00:06:30,020 --> 00:06:33,300
 about eight to 10 centimetres down from point F

154
00:06:33,300 --> 00:06:36,260
 at right angles to the B to F line

155
00:06:36,260 --> 00:06:40,700
 and mark the end of that line F2.

156
00:06:40,700 --> 00:06:42,780
 Now the back neck measurement.

157
00:06:42,780 --> 00:06:45,860
 This is measurement number 30 on the chart.

158
00:06:45,860 --> 00:06:48,260
 The back neck measurement is one of those

159
00:06:48,260 --> 00:06:51,060
 where you could take the half measurement from the center back

160
00:06:51,060 --> 00:06:55,020
 to the high neck point or measure from high neck point to high neck point

161
00:06:55,020 --> 00:06:56,580
 and divide by two.

162
00:06:56,580 --> 00:06:58,380
 But using that half measurement,

163
00:06:58,380 --> 00:07:03,540
 measure from point B on the B to C line and mark point G.

164
00:07:03,540 --> 00:07:08,140
 Draw another guideline from point G at right angles to the B, C line

165
00:07:08,140 --> 00:07:10,500
 and mark point G2.

166
00:07:10,500 --> 00:07:15,060
 The length of that line can be about eight to ten centimetres long.

167
00:07:15,060 --> 00:07:17,100
 Next is the shoulder slope back,

168
00:07:17,100 --> 00:07:19,820
 measurement number 26 on the chart.

169
00:07:19,820 --> 00:07:22,220
 Using your shoulder slope back measurement,

170
00:07:22,220 --> 00:07:25,980
 measure up diagonally from point A on the waistline

171
00:07:25,980 --> 00:07:29,340
 to touch the F to F2 guideline,

172
00:07:29,340 --> 00:07:33,620
 where it touches that guideline, mark point H.

173
00:07:33,620 --> 00:07:34,900
 Now just a point here.

174
00:07:34,900 --> 00:07:38,300
 Some instructions say to add a quarter of an centimetre

175
00:07:38,300 --> 00:07:40,860
 to your shoulder slope measurement for some ease.

176
00:07:40,860 --> 00:07:43,740
 I just find that when you take those measurements two or three times,

177
00:07:43,740 --> 00:07:47,580
 you can be out a quarter of a centimetre each time you take it.

178
00:07:47,580 --> 00:07:49,900
 My opinion is just take the body measurement.

179
00:07:49,900 --> 00:07:53,460
 When you make the 12, it should be obvious if you need a little bit more

180
00:07:53,460 --> 00:07:57,180
 and you can add it before you finalise your block.

181
00:07:57,180 --> 00:08:02,100
 Now a few slides back, we marked the back neck measurement from B to G.

182
00:08:02,100 --> 00:08:05,580
 Now the issue is that we've taken the measurement of a curve

183
00:08:05,580 --> 00:08:08,500
 and if you look at DD and left,

184
00:08:08,500 --> 00:08:11,540
 the curve is from the centre back neck to the high neck point

185
00:08:11,540 --> 00:08:15,300
 and we're plotting it on the block as a straight line.

186
00:08:15,300 --> 00:08:21,500
 So let's look at the next slide to see what the problem may be for some people.

187
00:08:21,500 --> 00:08:26,180
 Now the neck curve we need to draw is from point E to point G.

188
00:08:26,180 --> 00:08:30,980
 For DD, that curve from E to G ends up being much longer

189
00:08:30,980 --> 00:08:33,500
 than the measurement from B to G.

190
00:08:33,500 --> 00:08:37,060
 Now you may ask why then do the instructions plotted as a straight line

191
00:08:37,060 --> 00:08:39,980
 if the curve ends up being much longer?

192
00:08:39,980 --> 00:08:44,060
 Well for most people, or at least those who fall into the standard category,

193
00:08:44,060 --> 00:08:46,700
 it won't be a problem, it will work out.

194
00:08:46,700 --> 00:08:49,740
 DD actually happens to be non-standard.

195
00:08:49,740 --> 00:08:55,460
 I'll show you how it does work out for most people in the next slide with my block.

196
00:08:55,460 --> 00:08:59,420
 In my case, the length of the curve from E to G on the right

197
00:08:59,420 --> 00:09:03,220
 is only slightly longer than the straight line from B to G,

198
00:09:03,220 --> 00:09:05,460
 which is my original measurement.

199
00:09:05,460 --> 00:09:10,580
 And that bit of extra length gained in that curve is needed for ease.

200
00:09:10,580 --> 00:09:14,940
 This is one of the rare instances where I fall into the standard category.

201
00:09:14,940 --> 00:09:20,140
 And that standard is that there's only about one and a half centimetres

202
00:09:20,140 --> 00:09:24,100
 between points E and B.

203
00:09:24,100 --> 00:09:28,540
 What that means is I have only about one and a half centimetres difference

204
00:09:28,540 --> 00:09:32,740
 between my centre back and full length back measurements.

205
00:09:32,740 --> 00:09:39,580
 The green shaded areas on this slide shows the depth of the back net curve.

206
00:09:39,580 --> 00:09:44,220
 You can see that the shaded area on the left, my net curve is quite shallow.

207
00:09:44,220 --> 00:09:48,100
 With that shallow curve, the net curve ends up being slightly longer

208
00:09:48,100 --> 00:09:52,620
 than the body measurement and that slight increase is needed for ease.

209
00:09:52,620 --> 00:09:56,420
 For those who have more than that one and a half centimetre difference

210
00:09:56,420 --> 00:09:59,340
 between the centre back and the full length back,

211
00:09:59,340 --> 00:10:02,500
 they'll end up with a deep curve from E to G

212
00:10:02,500 --> 00:10:05,620
 that ends up longer than their back net measurement,

213
00:10:05,620 --> 00:10:08,140
 as it does for Dee Dee on the right.

214
00:10:08,140 --> 00:10:10,780
 She has nearly three centimetres difference

215
00:10:10,780 --> 00:10:14,260
 between her centre back and full length back measurements.

216
00:10:14,260 --> 00:10:17,740
 So if you fall into that category with a large difference

217
00:10:17,740 --> 00:10:22,020
 between your centre back and full length back measurements,

218
00:10:22,020 --> 00:10:24,220
 you'll need to do some adjusting and finessing

219
00:10:24,220 --> 00:10:26,820
 so that you don't end up with a gaping back neck

220
00:10:26,820 --> 00:10:32,300
 or that your high neck point doesn't end up too far out on your shoulder.

221
00:10:32,300 --> 00:10:36,540
 So basically, you'll have to draw that neckline curve in and measure it.

222
00:10:36,540 --> 00:10:39,820
 If the measurement from E to G ends up being a lot longer

223
00:10:39,820 --> 00:10:42,340
 or quite a bit longer than your actual measurement,

224
00:10:42,340 --> 00:10:46,660
 you'll need to move point G over to the left and try again.

225
00:10:46,660 --> 00:10:49,620
 And you'll need to finess it until you get the curve

226
00:10:49,620 --> 00:10:54,660
 from E to G to be about half a centimetre longer than your body measurement.

227
00:10:54,660 --> 00:10:56,700
 The next measurement is the shoulder length,

228
00:10:56,700 --> 00:10:59,300
 measurement number eight on the chart.

229
00:10:59,300 --> 00:11:01,060
 Take your shoulder length measurement

230
00:11:01,060 --> 00:11:04,620
 and add one and a quarter centimetres for a dart.

231
00:11:04,620 --> 00:11:08,420
 Using that total, shoulder length plus dart amount,

232
00:11:08,420 --> 00:11:13,460
 draw a line from point G at the neck to pass through point H,

233
00:11:13,460 --> 00:11:18,460
 the shoulder slope point, and mark the end of that line, point I.

234
00:11:18,460 --> 00:11:20,780
 I have actually put point I in brackets

235
00:11:20,780 --> 00:11:23,500
 because the capital I looks like a one

236
00:11:23,500 --> 00:11:25,220
 and the lower case seems to get lost.

237
00:11:25,220 --> 00:11:30,060
 So that's the only reason that it's there in brackets.

238
00:11:30,060 --> 00:11:33,060
 Now mark the midway point on the shoulder line.

239
00:11:33,060 --> 00:11:36,540
 So midway between point G and I

240
00:11:36,540 --> 00:11:40,820
 and mark that midpoint J.

241
00:11:40,820 --> 00:11:44,740
 Now the waist measurement, measurement number seven on the chart.

242
00:11:44,740 --> 00:11:46,620
 Moving down to your waistline,

243
00:11:46,620 --> 00:11:49,700
 take your waist measurement, that's your whole body circumference,

244
00:11:49,700 --> 00:11:51,660
 and divide it by four.

245
00:11:51,660 --> 00:11:55,860
 Then add three and three quarter centimetres for the dart.

246
00:11:55,860 --> 00:11:59,420
 Taking that total, waist plus dart,

247
00:11:59,420 --> 00:12:04,060
 measure from point A towards point D and mark point K.

248
00:12:04,060 --> 00:12:05,780
 Again, no ease at the moment.

249
00:12:05,780 --> 00:12:11,660
 We're going to add ease to the upper bust, bust, and waist at the very end.

250
00:12:11,660 --> 00:12:14,540
 From point K, measure down below the waistline

251
00:12:14,540 --> 00:12:18,700
 at right angles to the waistline and mark point K2.

252
00:12:18,700 --> 00:12:21,620
 The amount you measure down is a half a centimetre.

253
00:12:21,620 --> 00:12:23,380
 This will help with a waist curving

254
00:12:23,380 --> 00:12:26,860
 because the waist is not a completely straight line.

255
00:12:26,860 --> 00:12:29,260
 Now using your side seam length measurement,

256
00:12:29,260 --> 00:12:32,020
 that's measurement number nine on the measurement chart,

257
00:12:32,020 --> 00:12:35,140
 measure from point K2 just below the waist

258
00:12:35,140 --> 00:12:38,460
 up to touch the C to D line.

259
00:12:38,460 --> 00:12:42,860
 Where it touches the C to D line, mark point L1.

260
00:12:42,860 --> 00:12:46,180
 Then draw a guideline inwards for about five centimetres

261
00:12:46,180 --> 00:12:53,780
 from point L1 at right angles to the side seam line and mark point L2.

262
00:12:53,780 --> 00:12:56,620
 So this slide is just to remind you that when we drafted the front,

263
00:12:56,620 --> 00:13:00,460
 we did a similar thing in taking the waist down below the waistline

264
00:13:00,460 --> 00:13:02,620
 at the side seam for a smidge.

265
00:13:02,620 --> 00:13:06,580
 Then curving that up to blend to the straight waistline.

266
00:13:06,580 --> 00:13:08,980
 Doing this means that when we true the front and back,

267
00:13:08,980 --> 00:13:13,380
 we end up with a smooth flow through, as shown to the right at the top,

268
00:13:13,380 --> 00:13:18,060
 rather than the angular line shown at the bottom.

269
00:13:18,060 --> 00:13:22,300
 Now in drawing that side seam line up from the waist to touch the C to D line,

270
00:13:22,300 --> 00:13:25,020
 we have now defined the underarm point.

271
00:13:25,020 --> 00:13:27,780
 Point L1 is the underarm point.

272
00:13:27,780 --> 00:13:31,060
 This means we can now draw in the upper bust line.

273
00:13:31,060 --> 00:13:36,580
 So draw a line at right angles to the centre back line to touch point L1.

274
00:13:36,580 --> 00:13:40,740
 You can write upper bust on that line if you wish.

275
00:13:40,740 --> 00:13:44,220
 Next take your bust depth at side seam measurement.

276
00:13:44,220 --> 00:13:47,900
 That's number 17 on the measurement chart.

277
00:13:47,900 --> 00:13:52,860
 Measure down from the underarm point L1 and mark the bust level.

278
00:13:52,860 --> 00:13:56,900
 Draw a line from the centre back at right angles to the centre back line

279
00:13:56,900 --> 00:13:58,340
 to touch this point.

280
00:13:58,340 --> 00:14:01,180
 Now I actually neglected to give that point a letter,

281
00:14:01,180 --> 00:14:05,540
 but it should be okay because we are drawing the line there.

282
00:14:05,540 --> 00:14:09,540
 So now the across back measurement, measurement number 31 on the chart.

283
00:14:09,540 --> 00:14:11,900
 In my instructions for taking the measurements,

284
00:14:11,900 --> 00:14:17,140
 I said to take the across back measurement about halfway between the centre back neck

285
00:14:17,140 --> 00:14:19,100
 and the upper bust line.

286
00:14:19,100 --> 00:14:22,140
 So measure from point E, the centre back neck point,

287
00:14:22,140 --> 00:14:25,420
 to the upper bust line and divide that by two.

288
00:14:25,420 --> 00:14:31,220
 Using that measurement mark point M, which is the placement for the across back measurement.

289
00:14:31,220 --> 00:14:34,940
 Then using the across back measurement, which is on your chart,

290
00:14:34,940 --> 00:14:37,180
 divided by two for the half block,

291
00:14:37,180 --> 00:14:43,180
 measure inwards from point M and mark point N.

292
00:14:43,180 --> 00:14:47,660
 Now you can take a French curve and draw the armhole from point I at the shoulder

293
00:14:47,660 --> 00:14:52,540
 through point N at the across back down to point L1 at the underarm.

294
00:14:52,540 --> 00:14:56,260
 For DD, I can draw that in one pass with a curve.

295
00:14:56,260 --> 00:15:01,060
 You may need to draw two curves and blend it depending on your ruler.

296
00:15:01,060 --> 00:15:05,300
 Now if you end up with what seems to be a really large back armhole

297
00:15:05,300 --> 00:15:07,300
 and you have a rounded upper back,

298
00:15:07,300 --> 00:15:10,860
 chances are you'll have some excess E's in the back armhole.

299
00:15:10,860 --> 00:15:16,060
 What you'll need to do in the fitting stage is to pinch the excess E's out and measure it.

300
00:15:16,060 --> 00:15:19,060
 Then move that excess into the shoulder dart.

301
00:15:19,060 --> 00:15:23,260
 We haven't constructed the shoulder dart yet, but we'll be doing that in a bit.

302
00:15:23,260 --> 00:15:26,260
 However, that fitting does need to be done in the 12 stage

303
00:15:26,260 --> 00:15:30,980
 because it's hard to determine what size dart you need in the shoulder.

304
00:15:30,980 --> 00:15:34,100
 So you always start with the basic amount,

305
00:15:34,100 --> 00:15:40,860
 and in the 12 fitting stage you can increase that shoulder dart width.

306
00:15:40,860 --> 00:15:45,100
 Now we're going to place the waist dart and mark the width of the dart

307
00:15:45,100 --> 00:15:49,100
 and draw the center line of the waist dart up to the upper bust.

308
00:15:49,100 --> 00:15:53,020
 Now if you're unsure of where to place your back waist dart,

309
00:15:53,020 --> 00:15:55,820
 there are some general guides on the screen.

310
00:15:55,820 --> 00:16:01,620
 Basically between 7cm and 9cm from the center back waist.

311
00:16:01,620 --> 00:16:06,700
 When you make your 12, see if you like it there and move it accordingly if you don't.

312
00:16:06,700 --> 00:16:14,020
 So taking that measurement, measure across from point A on the waistline towards point D and mark point O.

313
00:16:14,020 --> 00:16:19,100
 Then measure from point O for the width of the dart and mark point P.

314
00:16:19,100 --> 00:16:25,620
 We allowed for a 3 and 3/4 centimeter dart when we marked point K,

315
00:16:25,620 --> 00:16:31,100
 so from point O to P should be 3 and 3/4 centimetres.

316
00:16:31,100 --> 00:16:36,580
 In the middle of that dart, draw a straight line up to the upper bust line and mark point Q.

317
00:16:36,580 --> 00:16:43,980
 Make sure that that line from the middle of the dart to point Q is at right angles to the waistline.

318
00:16:43,980 --> 00:16:53,700
 Draw the first dart leg from point Q through point O and go a half a centimetre below the waistline and mark point O2.

319
00:16:53,700 --> 00:17:02,220
 Draw the other dart line from point Q to go through point P to go half a centimetre below the waistline and mark point P2.

320
00:17:02,220 --> 00:17:07,980
 Check that those two lines are the same length, they need to be the same length.

321
00:17:07,980 --> 00:17:14,380
 Draw the waist curve in as shown, you will need to extend the mid dart line down below the waist.

322
00:17:14,380 --> 00:17:24,340
 Then with the help of a curved ruler, draw a curved line from point A at centre back to pass through point O2 and touch the mid dart line that you've extended down.

323
00:17:24,340 --> 00:17:29,700
 Then turn the ruler over to get the same curve from the mid dart line through point P2.

324
00:17:29,700 --> 00:17:36,220
 Then draw another curve from point P2 to the side seam point K2.

325
00:17:36,220 --> 00:17:42,300
 In the measurement video, I suggested that you take your back armhole depth a number of ways for checking purposes.

326
00:17:42,300 --> 00:17:46,220
 These are measurements 27, 28 and 29 on the chart.

327
00:17:46,220 --> 00:17:53,700
 So centre back to upper bust, high neck point to upper bust and shoulder point to upper bust on the shoulder slope line.

328
00:17:53,700 --> 00:18:00,900
 Now we didn't actually use any of these measurements to get the armhole depth, but now it's the time to check those measurements that they do work out.

329
00:18:00,900 --> 00:18:05,940
 It would just give you an idea of whether you've made some major mistakes.

330
00:18:05,940 --> 00:18:12,060
 Now if you do actually plot those and they all end up on the same level but not at the upper bust line,

331
00:18:12,060 --> 00:18:17,780
 then what you'd need to do is check your shoulder slope and full length front before continuing.

332
00:18:17,780 --> 00:18:22,820
 If after checking the shoulder slope and the full length front you come up with the same measurements,

333
00:18:22,820 --> 00:18:28,620
 then just draft the block and draw the lines on it and check it at the 12 stage.

334
00:18:28,620 --> 00:18:30,940
 Now we'll construct the shoulder dart.

335
00:18:30,940 --> 00:18:39,540
 Draw a guideline from point Q, the waist dart point and point J on the mid shoulder.

336
00:18:39,540 --> 00:18:46,500
 From point J, measure down that guideline for seven and a half centimetres and mark the dart point R.

337
00:18:46,500 --> 00:18:53,340
 Now when I say seven and a half centimetres, with all these things, that's the starting point that may need to be finessed.

338
00:18:53,340 --> 00:18:55,620
 It may be different from person to person.

339
00:18:55,620 --> 00:19:00,940
 Didi needed a dart that was longer than seven and a half centimetres.

340
00:19:00,940 --> 00:19:10,060
 Now draw a dart along the shoulder line with J at the centre and make that dart one and a quarter centimetres wide.

341
00:19:10,060 --> 00:19:19,420
 Now draw a dart leg from point R through point S and go beyond point S for a quarter of a centimetre and mark point U.

342
00:19:19,420 --> 00:19:25,420
 Measure that dart leg from point R to point U and draw the second dart leg to match that length.

343
00:19:25,420 --> 00:19:33,540
 So from point R through point T and mark point V. Also to be able to finish off the shaping of the shoulder line,

344
00:19:33,540 --> 00:19:38,020
 extend the mid dart line out for a couple of centimetres.

345
00:19:38,020 --> 00:19:46,500
 Then to draw the shoulder line, start at point I and draw a straight line to point V and continue until you reach the mid dart line.

346
00:19:46,500 --> 00:19:52,180
 Then draw from the mid dart line to point U, then to point G.

347
00:19:52,180 --> 00:19:56,980
 On the left is the final shape of the milage because it still doesn't have any E's.

348
00:19:56,980 --> 00:20:02,380
 And the shape is from point A at the waist, up to point E, centre back neck point,

349
00:20:02,380 --> 00:20:10,660
 around the neck curve to point G at the shoulder, then to point I through points U and V on the shoulder to point I.

350
00:20:10,660 --> 00:20:19,700
 The armhole curve down to L1, down to the waist K2 and then the waist curve back to A.

351
00:20:19,700 --> 00:20:25,060
 And on the right in pink is the shape without the emphasis on the points.

352
00:20:25,060 --> 00:20:28,540
 Now this is basically your milage for the back.

353
00:20:28,540 --> 00:20:33,540
 If you do sew this up and it doesn't fit, part of that will be that you have no E's.

354
00:20:33,540 --> 00:20:38,020
 You really do need a little bit of E's in order to be able to do it up.

355
00:20:38,020 --> 00:20:42,900
 It will be difficult to pin up if it's made to your exact measurements.

356
00:20:42,900 --> 00:20:45,060
 So now we'll add E's to the side seam.

357
00:20:45,060 --> 00:20:51,140
 If you look at the graphic on the right-hand side, the pink line, the pink side seam line is the milage side seam

358
00:20:51,140 --> 00:20:57,340
 and the blue line to the right is the side seam line for the sleeveless block after E's is added.

359
00:20:57,340 --> 00:21:03,980
 More E's is added to the upper bust and that tapers down on an angle to the waist where less E's is added.

360
00:21:03,980 --> 00:21:10,660
 The waist E's, which is the same for the sleeveless and sleeves block, is two and a half centimetre across the whole block.

361
00:21:10,660 --> 00:21:17,140
 We're not going to distribute that evenly just because 0.63 of a centimetre is not that easy to measure.

362
00:21:17,140 --> 00:21:21,700
 We added one centimetre to the front which leaves one and a half centimetres for the back.

363
00:21:21,700 --> 00:21:24,900
 That's three-quarters of a centimetre for the half block.

364
00:21:24,900 --> 00:21:32,660
 So move out from the waist side seam point K2 for three-quarters of a centimetre and mark point X.

365
00:21:32,660 --> 00:21:39,140
 For the upper busties, the sleeveless block will have seven and a half centimetres and that's across the whole block.

366
00:21:39,140 --> 00:21:41,900
 We've already added two and a half of that to the front.

367
00:21:41,900 --> 00:21:46,620
 So now there is a remainder of five centimetres E's to add to the back.

368
00:21:46,620 --> 00:21:49,540
 That is two and a half centimetres for the half block.

369
00:21:49,540 --> 00:21:53,500
 We will also lower the armhole one and a half centimetres.

370
00:21:53,500 --> 00:22:02,660
 So firstly, measure down from point L1 on the L1 to K line to drop the armhole one and a half centimetres.

371
00:22:02,660 --> 00:22:13,140
 So measure down one and a half centimetres, then at right angles to the L1 to K line, measure out two and a half centimetres and mark point Y.

372
00:22:13,140 --> 00:22:20,020
 Draw a line from point Y to point X. That is the side seam line for the sleeveless block.

373
00:22:20,020 --> 00:22:28,500
 You'll then need to redraw the armhole from point N to point Y with a French curve.

374
00:22:28,500 --> 00:22:34,540
 So I suggest that you measure the bust line to see how much E's you've ended up with at the bust level.

375
00:22:34,540 --> 00:22:37,460
 You need to exclude the dart, obviously.

376
00:22:37,460 --> 00:22:45,860
 Now you need to compare this measurement to your body bust art back and see what the difference is to see how much E's you've ended up with.

377
00:22:45,860 --> 00:22:50,500
 So the standard amount, so the amount that you're aiming for or hoping for,

378
00:22:50,500 --> 00:22:57,220
 two and a half to five centimetres for the sleeveless block and later on you can check again for the sleeved block.

379
00:22:57,220 --> 00:23:01,860
 That's five to seven and a half centimetres for the sleeved block.

380
00:23:01,860 --> 00:23:09,380
 Now again this is for the whole block. Two things here, you may end up with more or less E's than this.

381
00:23:09,380 --> 00:23:16,980
 And in the next slide I'll show you how D, D and I end up with very different amounts of E's in the back at the bust.

382
00:23:16,980 --> 00:23:26,020
 But even if you end up with a standard amount, it may be too much and even if you end up with a standard amount, it may not be enough.

383
00:23:26,020 --> 00:23:35,620
 I plan on doing another video on E's but I'll quickly cover four reasons why it's difficult for me to give instructions that will give you

384
00:23:35,620 --> 00:23:38,980
 the exact amount of E's that you need.

385
00:23:38,980 --> 00:23:46,500
 One, you may have taken your measurements too loosely, so rather than your body measurements you already have E's built into your measurements

386
00:23:46,500 --> 00:23:49,700
 and therefore you will end up with too much E's.

387
00:23:49,700 --> 00:23:57,220
 Two, the smaller you are the less E's you need. We've added a set amount rather than a proportionate amount of E's

388
00:23:57,220 --> 00:24:04,660
 and that is customary for block making instructions but five centimetres on a size four is a lot more proportionally

389
00:24:04,660 --> 00:24:08,260
 than five centimetres for someone who is size 20.

390
00:24:08,260 --> 00:24:14,420
 So the smaller you are, chances are the more E's that you will end up with more E's than you need.

391
00:24:14,420 --> 00:24:21,300
 Third reason, the more fat you have, the more E's you need. Fat spreads and your body shape changes with movement.

392
00:24:21,300 --> 00:24:30,660
 So for example, when you sit down, your fat will move around and something that is loose under the bust when you're standing can become tight when you sit down.

393
00:24:30,660 --> 00:24:36,500
 So again, the slimmer you are, the less E's you need, the more fat you are, the more E's you need.

394
00:24:36,500 --> 00:24:46,580
 And for the most important, E's is a very individual preference. Some people like things tight, some people cannot stand tight things.

395
00:24:46,580 --> 00:24:55,220
 All of these things taken together mean that it's not possible for me to give instructions for adding E's that will suit every single person.

396
00:24:55,220 --> 00:25:11,140
 So that is why I have this system where you draft them a large, you can see where the E's is that you're adding and you can choose to shave bits of that E's off if that E's is too much, and you'll also be able to add E's if it's not enough.

397
00:25:11,140 --> 00:25:20,900
 So now I want to show you how Didi and I have ended up with very different amounts of E's at the bust, even though we added the same amount of E's at the upper bust and the waist.

398
00:25:20,900 --> 00:25:27,700
 Now Didi and I have very similar bust measurements, but very different upper bust measurements and very different arcs.

399
00:25:27,700 --> 00:25:42,580
 If you look at Didi's block on the left, her upper bust arc, that is from A to B, is larger than her bust arc, that is C to D. Note that D ends up to the left of the rectangle of her block.

400
00:25:42,580 --> 00:25:52,580
 So the orange square indicates how much E's she has in the bust. She has some E's within that rectangle, that is her block base, plus some E's outside of it.

401
00:25:52,580 --> 00:26:00,580
 She ends up with one and a half centimetre E's in the half back, which means three centimetres for the full back.

402
00:26:00,580 --> 00:26:15,580
 My upper bust arc, A to B, is exactly the same measurement as my bust arc from C to D. So when I take into account that dart, it means D extends past my basic rectangle.

403
00:26:15,580 --> 00:26:29,580
 So I end up with less than a quarter centimetre E's for the half back. That means less than half a centimetre for the full back compared to Didi's three centimetres for the full back, which is a significant difference.

404
00:26:29,580 --> 00:26:41,580
 And you do need to add this to the front E's to see how much you've got for your total block, but I'm showing you that I have much less E's than Didi does at the bust level following the same instructions.

405
00:26:41,580 --> 00:26:48,580
 On the right is my block from the last slide, where I showed you that I ended up with much less E's than Didi.

406
00:26:48,580 --> 00:26:56,580
 Now if after I make a twirl, I decide that that E's is not enough, one way I can get some extra E's is to reduce the height of the dart.

407
00:26:56,580 --> 00:27:11,580
 So on the left hand side you can see that if I reduce the height of the dart, I gained some extra E's. If that is still insufficient, I could also add some at the upper bust and draw a line from that point down to the waist to gain a bit more E's at the bust level.

408
00:27:11,580 --> 00:27:20,580
 For those who may be wondering, isn't it possible to add E's at the bust without adding E's at the upper bust? Well yes, as shown by the dashed line around my block.

409
00:27:20,580 --> 00:27:29,580
 If I extend at the bust level without increasing the upper bust, I end up with a curved side seam. There is nothing wrong with a curved side seam if you want to go that way.

410
00:27:29,580 --> 00:27:36,580
 If you look at pattern making textbooks from 100 years ago or more, they used curves a lot. Well not only the side seam but the shoulder seam and the center front as well.

411
00:27:36,580 --> 00:27:43,580
 In the graphic to the right, the red line is a curved shoulder seam and the blue line is a curved side seam for a jacket.

412
00:27:43,580 --> 00:27:50,580
 There is nothing to stop you adding more E's at the bust and leaving an upper bust the same and having a curved side seam.

413
00:27:50,580 --> 00:27:58,580
 But I'm not going to do that and so all of my instructions will continue with a straight side seam.

414
00:27:58,580 --> 00:28:06,580
 So back to Dee Dee's block. This is where we left off. The pink line is her moolage and the blue line is her sleeveless block.

415
00:28:06,580 --> 00:28:13,580
 So I ended up with far less E's than Dee Dee and I talked about adding E's for my situation if it's necessary.

416
00:28:13,580 --> 00:28:22,580
 Chances are that Dee Dee has more E's than she needs. So if you like Dee Dee and would like to reduce your busties, come in from the underarm side seam for a quarter of an inch or so

417
00:28:22,580 --> 00:28:26,580
 and remove the sliver shown in yellow. It goes down to nothing at the waist.

418
00:28:26,580 --> 00:28:31,580
 This will reduce the busties by about half inch across the whole back.

419
00:28:31,580 --> 00:28:37,580
 Of course this also reduces the E's at the upper bust but as I said for Dee Dee this is probably necessary.

420
00:28:37,580 --> 00:28:40,580
 She probably has no fat on her whatsoever.

421
00:28:40,580 --> 00:28:45,580
 You do not have to reduce the front E's the same amount as you reduce the back.

422
00:28:45,580 --> 00:28:51,580
 Do check though how much busties you end up across the whole block and you may want to reduce the front a little as well.

423
00:28:51,580 --> 00:28:58,580
 In the end you should have at least one inch E's at the bust level and that's assuming you've taken your body measurements correctly.

424
00:28:58,580 --> 00:29:04,580
 That is firmly rather than loosely. Now someone might ask well we started by adding the E's unevenly.

425
00:29:04,580 --> 00:29:10,580
 If we added the E's evenly to begin with Dee Dee's back would have not had so much E's.

426
00:29:10,580 --> 00:29:22,580
 Well two things in response to that. One Dee Dee's E's would still need to be reduced and maybe in that case if the E's had been added evenly rather than two thirds to the back and one thirds to the front.

427
00:29:22,580 --> 00:29:30,580
 She would need to take some of the front and the back. But number two well that would work okay for Dee Dee but not my figure.

428
00:29:30,580 --> 00:29:37,580
 Remember I ended up with very little busties even after adding two thirds of the upper bust E's to the back.

429
00:29:37,580 --> 00:29:45,580
 The reason I chose the distribution of E's works better for my type of figure is that my focus has always been on those who have large pattern making bust cups.

430
00:29:45,580 --> 00:29:59,580
 That is smaller up and bust in proportion to the bust because that's where most block making instructions are lacking and don't end up with good results for the small upper bust and large bust figure.

431
00:29:59,580 --> 00:30:07,580
 So now we'll add the E's for the sleeved block. I will just continue with Dee Dee's original sleeveless draft.

432
00:30:07,580 --> 00:30:24,580
 I suggest that you make your sleeveless 12 first and fit it, make any changes and then continue with these steps from the final side seam line that may or may not include changes depending on whether you've reduced or increased the E's.

433
00:30:24,580 --> 00:30:39,580
 The upper bust E's for the sleeved block is 12 and a half centimetres. We have already added seven and a half for the sleeveless block so there's five centimetres remaining. We'll add two thirds to the back and one third to the front as we did before.

434
00:30:39,580 --> 00:30:57,580
 So that means three centimetres to the whole back, one and a half centimetres to the half block. The sleeved block is also lowered a little bit so from point y we'll measure down for one centimetre and out one and a half centimetre to point z.

435
00:30:57,580 --> 00:31:13,580
 So measure down from point y on the sleeveless side seam line for one centimetre, then at right angles to that side seam line, measure out for one and a half centimetres and mark point z, then draw a line from point z to point K2 at the waist.

436
00:31:13,580 --> 00:31:27,580
 To draw the armhole for the sleeved block, you'll need to add one centimetre to the shoulder length and a half a centimetre to the across chest as we did for the front. You will also need to draft the actual sleeve to go with the sleeved block.

437
00:31:27,580 --> 00:31:41,580
 Now before you draft the sleeve, you may also want to check the amount of E's at the bust level for this sleeved block and make some adjustments so that you do only have between five and seven and a half centimetres E's at the bust level.

438
00:31:41,580 --> 00:31:56,580
 If you are really thin with no body fat and you let things really closely fitting, you might want to reduce that down to between three and a half and five centimetres, but if you're large and you do have quite a bit of body fat, you may want to try the seven and a half centimetres.

439
00:31:56,580 --> 00:32:12,580
 Here are three blocks for comparison purposes, with all of them having both sleeved and sleeveless versions. On the left is my block, in the middle is a standard block, in a size 14 and on the right is DD.

440
00:32:12,580 --> 00:32:26,580
 I recommend you draw all the lines from the block on the twale. Doing this means you can see where you've made mistakes and also it's much easier to see where the adjustments need to be made.

441
00:32:26,580 --> 00:32:46,580
 Now a note on the shoulder slope line, on your block it's not drawn to the shoulder tip because that's your across back measurement and in actual, in reality, when you sew up the dart, then point I would end up being where point H is on the block.

442
00:32:46,580 --> 00:33:04,580
 But when you draw that line on your twale, it makes sense to draw it from the centre back waist to the actual shoulder tip. From here on is some general information on truing the front and the back and finishing off your block. This was also included in the bodice front video.

443
00:33:04,580 --> 00:33:26,580
 When we finish both the front and the back, we need to check that the lengths of adjacent pieces match and also check that there is a nice flow through in the curves. If you need to increase the length of anything, you may need to stick on little bits of paper. I'm not going to be doing that in my example, but just be aware you may have to.

444
00:33:26,580 --> 00:33:37,580
 So firstly, we'll do the side seam. Put the back and front blocks together at the side seam waist. Check that there's a smooth curve at the waist.

445
00:33:37,580 --> 00:33:45,580
 Then check the side seam length. Firstly from the waist up to the dart leg. Then check that the remainder matches up.

446
00:33:45,580 --> 00:33:49,580
 Check that there is a smooth curve through the armhole.

447
00:33:49,580 --> 00:34:05,580
 Then match the front and back at the high neck point to check the neck line curve. While you're there, mark the shoulder dart placement from the back block onto the front block so that you can check the shoulder length.

448
00:34:05,580 --> 00:34:21,580
 Move the front block to the other dart leg and check the shoulder lengths are the same. This is especially important when drafting the three options together, the malage and the sleeveless and the sleeve. You may have traced off the sleeveless block on the front and then accidentally trace off the sleeve version in the back.

449
00:34:21,580 --> 00:34:25,580
 So definitely always check your shoulder lengths match.

450
00:34:25,580 --> 00:34:41,580
 Then check the flow through curve of the armhole. When you have your final front and back blocks, don't forget to mark and notch the dart legs, label the block, put all the relevant information on it, maybe including the date you drafted it.

451
00:34:41,580 --> 00:34:55,580
 Note whether it's a sleeveless block or the sleeveless block or the malage. Now I did hear a patent maker say that you don't put the grainline on the block, you put that on the pattern, but I like to have it on my block to remind me to put it on the pattern.

452
00:34:55,580 --> 00:35:08,580
 Sometimes I forget and then I get to putting my pattern pieces on the fabric and realise I haven't drawn the grainline on there. So yes, I definitely prefer to put the grainline on the block as a reminder.

453
00:35:08,580 --> 00:35:17,580
 So here are some final blocks, not DDs, but this is what the final blocks look like. These ones don't have the bust line or upper bust mark.

454
00:35:17,580 --> 00:35:27,580
 That was needed during the drafting process for making the twile and getting the measurements right. On the actual blocks, you don't need them.

455
00:35:27,580 --> 00:35:36,580
 So this is the end of the video. In April I hope to get up the bodice booklet as well as the first of the variation on the silhouette videos and that one is on contouring.

456
